  {
    "comprehension": null,
    "direction": null,
    "content": "<p>Addressing of a $32 K \\times 16$ memory is realized using a single decoder. The minimum number of AND gates required for the decoder is :</p>",
    "options": [
      {
        "identifier": "A",
        "content": "<p>$2^{19}$</p>\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "B",
        "content": "<p>$2^8$</p>\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "C",
        "content": "<p>$2^{32}$</p>\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "D",
        "content": "<p>$2^{15}$</p>"
      }
    ],
    "correct_options": [
      "D"
    ],
    "answer": null,
    "explanation": "<p>We have a memory of <strong>$32K \\times 16$</strong>.</p>\n\n<h3>Step 1: Interpret what $32K \\times 16$ means</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><p>$32K = 32 \\times 1024 = 32768$ <strong>memory locations</strong> (or words).</p></li>\n<li><p>Each location stores <strong>16 bits</strong> (word size).</p></li>\n</ul>\n<p>So, there are $32768$ addressable words.</p>\n\n<h3>Step 2: How many address lines are needed?</h3>\n<p>To address $32768$ words, we need  </p>\n<p>$ 2^{15} = 32768 $</p>\n<p>So, there are <strong>15 address lines</strong>.</p>\n\n<h3>Step 3: Decoder function</h3>\n<p>A <strong>decoder</strong> converts binary address inputs to one-hot outputs.</p>\n<p>For 15 input lines ⇒ $2^{15}$ outputs.</p>\n<p>Each output corresponds to one word (one memory location).</p>\n\n<h3>Step 4: Number of AND gates in the decoder</h3>\n<p>A simple implementation of an <strong>n-to-2ⁿ decoder</strong> uses <strong>2ⁿ AND gates</strong>,  </p>\n<p>each AND gate detects one unique n-bit input pattern.</p>\n<p>Hence, for <strong>15 address inputs</strong>, the decoder requires:</p>\n<p>$ 2^{15} = 32768 \\text{ AND gates.} $</p>\n\n<p>✅ <strong>Final Answer:</strong></p>\n<p>$ \\boxed{2^{15}} $</p>\n<p><strong>Correct Option: D</strong></p>",
    "topic": null,
    "year": 2021,
    "yearKey": "gate-ece-2021",
    "difficulty": null
  },
